  "opinion": "As a woman in my sixties who's spent most of her life in Bari, Italy, I've seen how science has evolved but also how it's still out of reach for many. Growing up with a mother who had only lower secondary education and a father with a PhD, I learned early that knowledge isn't just about formal schooling—it's about who you know and where you're from. When I was a child, my father would take me to the library, but even there, the books were mostly written by men. Today, I work as a cleaner, and I often see the same faces in the labs and universities—men in white coats, women in the background. The gender gap in science isn't just about numbers; it's about the feeling of being invisible. I worry about my grandchildren, who might grow up thinking science is only for boys. We should address it by creating spaces where girls feel safe to explore without judgment. In my community, we have a small garden where kids can learn about plants and nature, and I've noticed more girls participating now. But it's not enough. We need to make sure that when a girl wants to study physics or chemistry, she doesn't have to hide her curiosity. My anxiety makes me think twice about speaking up, but I believe that if we start small—like in schools or local clubs—it can change. The key isn't just policies but changing the way we see science as something for everyone, not just a select few.",
